Package edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic

Class True

java.lang.Object
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.Disjunction<Clause<Atom>>
edu.uky.cs.nil.sabre.logic.True
All Implemented Interfaces:
Expression, Logical, Parameter, Proposition, Simplifiable, Typed, Value, Countable, Unique, Serializable, Comparable<Logical>, Iterable<Clause<Atom>>
public final class True extends Disjunction<Clause<Atom>> implements Unique, Value
True is one of two singleton values of type boolean that represents the opposite of false. True is a disjunction of one empty clause, which means it is in disjunctive normal form. True is always defined and does not belong to any specific universe. True always returns itself when evaluated.
Author:
Stephen G. Ware

    • simplify

      public True simplify()
      Description copied from class: Disjunction
      If any argument to this disjunction can be simplified to true, this method returns true. If any argument to this disjunction can be simplified to false it is removed. If there are no arguments, or if all arguments can be removed, this method returns false. If exactly one argument remains after simplification, it is returned instead of a disjunction. If two or more arguments remain, they will be put into their natural order.

This method is used to simplify expressions by converting anything which is not valued into valued expressions and moving any conditionals outside of the expression.
